Thank you for your feedback. The problem with the food appearing in the first TrainingArea instead of the correct TrainingArea lies in the `ResetFoods()` method. When you remove the eaten food references using `foodInstances.RemoveAll(food => food == null)`, you are only removing the null references from the list, but not updating the actual list of food instances.

To fix this, update the `ResetFoods()` method by not making a separate list for eaten food but directly creating a new Food instance where the eaten Food was null.

Here's the modified `ResetFoods()` method in TrainingArea.cs:

```csharp
public void ResetFoods()
{
    for (int i = 0; i < foodInstances.Count; i++)
    {
        GameObject food = foodInstances[i];
        if (food != null)
        {
            food.transform.localPosition = GetValidSpawnPosition();
        }
        else
        {
            Vector3 spawnPosition = GetValidSpawnPosition();
            GameObject foodInstance = Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition, Quaternion.identity, transform);
            foodInstance.layer = LayerMask.NameToLayer("Food");
            foodInstances[i] = foodInstance;
        }
    }
}
```

This implementation reuses the same index in the `foodInstances` list for spawning new Food instances when the previous instance is null. That ensures that the currently spawned instances of Food are tracked correctly for each TrainingArea.

